Today's 8x10 acrylic on canvas paper (unframed) will have a starting bid of $25, and bidding will close at 2:47 EST tomorrow. The details are below. In case I am not able to attend the end of an auction in person, I go back and look at timestamps to determine the winner. .
Please note that orders will all be shipped June 10th as we are currently in the middle of a move down to sunny St. Petersburg, FL and we will be doing our best to get everything out of boxes as soon as possible. Thank you for your understanding!
.
The details:
Highest bid wins. Here are the rules:  Comment with a bid on the picture in USD and your email address (you only need to type it once, and feel free to DM or email it to me for privacy concerns). Your bid excludes shipping. All shipping is $5 flat fee. Only bid in whole numbers. $0.50 bids will be deleted and ignored. You are welcome to pay in USD via PayPal or a CC on the invoice.  Keep checking that no one has outbid you if you want the artwork.
.
.
After 24 hours, I will announce the winners through tagging on the image. Then I will send you an email with the winning bids, asking for your postal address and method of payment. Then an invoice.  You must pay within 2 days, otherwise it goes to the next bid.
Everything has a starter bid. If no one bids on it, it will be destroyed via a fun method that everyone enjoys.  Questions?
.

Photo by 8 years old Zoey.
My soul among the grass
each blade is a heaven
precious gem is in the light
diamond is the seed  in the soil
these treasure are beyond measure
in the soft words of grass
wisdom grows in the humility
greatness leap in the fleeting moment
those teachings are pure gold
extending the lease of breath on earth 
Study, 6/13/2019
Ai Qiu

First time this work has been offered at auction 🤩

Pablo Picasso, Homme à La Pipe, 1968, oil on canvas.

Taking on the persona of a musketeer, a recurrent iconography in the works of Picasso in the late 60’s until his death in 1973, the figure of the smoker in this painting is a reference to the artist himself, often photographed at the time smoking a cigarette.

We recently sold this Francis Picabia composition, circa 1924 for $81,250!⠀
.⠀
Born in France in 1879, Picabia was associated with the Cubist, Dada, and Surrealist art movements before returning to figurative painting in 1925.⠀
.⠀
This graphite composition is a superb example of the artist's practice and evolving art movements of the early 20th century.⠀
.⠀

Integrated in the late fifties in Informalism and always eager to surprise, experimented with textures, objects and colors to provide realistic impressions to fundamentally abstract compositions. His work is forceful, even aggressive in regard to colors, light and density of matter.

Eντυπωσιακή απόδοση τοπίου τόσο ως προς τη σύλληψη όσο και ως προς τη σιγουριά του δυναμισμού με τον οποίο πραγματώνεται. Η σαφήνεια με την οποία οργανώνεται η σύνθεση συνυπάρχει με την επανεγγραφή τεχνοτροπικών χαρακτηριστικών που σφραγίζουν γενικότερα τη δημιουργία του Μαλέα.
Ο τρόπος που ο ζωγράφος χειρίζεται την πυκνή πάστα του χρώματος αποτυπώνει τις χειρονομίες του, καθώς είναι εμφανείς οι διαδρομές των εργαλείων που το άπλωσαν, επιτρέποντας στον θεατή να παρακολουθήσει έτσι και τη διαδρομή της δημιουργίας του έργου. Το εξαιρετικό έργο διακρίνεται από το ότι ο συνολικός τρόπος της απόδοσής του εμφυσά μνημειακό περιεχόμενο, επιβεβαιώνοντας τη σημασία της καλλιτεχνικής μορφής του Μαλέα ως μεγάλου δασκάλου στην ιστορία της ελληνικής τέχνης.

Θα βρείτε τον Ελληνικό Κατάλογο της επόμενης δημοπρασίας μας εδώ: —> http://bit.ly/2wmQePe

Behind the Scenes in an Auction House - How to photograph a 36 square meter antique Persian rug:
As we had no room large and high enough to comfortably fit our photographer and get a decent angle, we had to get creative. It took a full road blockade, 10 employees and a second-floor window to finally get a good catalogue shot done for this exceptional piece. 
You can view the result and lot information on www.auktionshaus-Wendl.com.

Hinter den Kulissen im Auktionshaus: Wie fotografiert man einen antiken, persischen 36-Quadratmeter-Teppich? 
Da wir keinen Raum zur Verfügung hatten, der groß und hoch genug ist um unserem Fotografen bequem unterzubringen und einen angemessenen Winkel abzubilden, mussten wir kreativ werden. Dank einer Straßensperre, 10 helfenden Mitarbeitern und einem Fenster im 2. Stock gelang uns endlich ein gutes Katalogfoto. 
Das Ergebnis und alle Details zu dieser Antiquität können unter www.auktionshaus-Wendl.de eingesehen werden.
